  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Dutch Neck sprang up in the mid‑1700s after land purchases in the 1730s and 1740s by early settlers.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.westwindsorhistory.com/dutchneck.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "By the 1780s the name “Dutch Neck” was in use, pointing to Dutch pioneers and a “neck of the woods.”",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18,
        19
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.westwindsorhistory.com/dutchneck.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Dutch Neck Presbyterian Church graveyard, with roughly 1,200 graves, contains the oldest stone dated 1771.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23,
        24
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.westwindsorhistory.com/dutchneck.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Jacob Bergen’s inn, now a private residence, hosted West Windsor’s first town meetings in 1797 and for eleven years after.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        26,
        27
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.westwindsorhistory.com/dutchneck.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Dutch Neck sits where South Mill and Village Roads East/West cross, a 1750s route that linked Allentown to Princeton.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16,
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.westwindsorhistory.com/dutchneck.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The Slayback homestead at 542 Village Road West, dating to the 1750s or 1760s, is one of the few colonial homes still standing.",
